28-year-old cook found dead in San Francisco shopping center
The 28-year-old, who recently moved to San Francisco, was found dead in the stairs of the local shopping center this week.
However, the victim’s brother says that he can’t imagine someone who would like to hurt him, noting: “Finally, he was doing good.”
“The body found in Westfield Mall on Wednesday morning was identified as a 28-year-old resident of San Francisco Frank Galicia,” San Francisco’s Bureau of Forensic Examination Reported.
The San Francisco Police Department says that the death was classified as murder and investigation is ongoing.
The victim’s brother, Luis Galicia, told the KGO channel ABC in San Francisco that Frank, the former divorce chef in Boston, got his dream job as a cook at the San Francisco’s Sons & Daughters restaurant six months ago.
A spokesperson for Sons & Daughters said they were “shocked and depressed” by his death.
“We are a small team that works as a friendly family and will be very missed,” the spokesman said.
Our thoughts and condolences to Frank's family and friends during this difficult period.
Luis Galicia said that Frank first stayed in the hostels, but recently, "Finally, he's been doing business."
“He found the apartment, he was dating a girl,” Luis Galicia told KGO.
Luis Galicia said he couldn’t imagine anyone who would like to hurt his younger brother.
He had a good soul and a big heart.
His way of contacting his family has always been to make us some dish, prepare us dinner,” Luis Galicia said.
He never wanted to be involved in any quarrel.
He was a brother who sailed with the flow.
“With all the bad things that happens to this world, it was the uncut diamond that shone brightly every day,” he said.
Anyone who owns the information is asked to call the SFPD Hotline at number 415-575-4444.
Churkin said that the meeting of the UN Security Council on Crimea was useful.
