A French court has rejected Calé’s offer to demolish dozens of homemade shops and restaurants in the Jungle camp, where thousands of refugees live.
At this week’s court hearings, Calé authorities said that the state should be able to demolish a total of 72 homemade shops, where people inside the camp sell goods, from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer to cut or sell tea for 50 cents (40p) or simple meals for a few euros in homemade restaurants.
Cale Prefecture said that these places should be demolished because they are a parallel economy that does not pay taxes, and because they carry fire and sanitary risks.
Humanitarian groups told the court that shops and restaurants are vital, stating that the free meals offered by the pro-government association and other groups do not provide enough food for the growing number of camp.
They said homemade shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to those in need.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis to expel the people driving 72 homemade stores, but said that the problems of Calais’ prefecture “were completely clear.”
Judge Jean-François Molla said that groceries, cafes and restaurants played a much bigger role than just feeding people who "live in extremely shaky conditions."
He said that the spaces were provided with calm points of the meeting of refugees and volunteers.
One of the sites that was at risk of demolition was the children's cafe book of the camp, which does not work for profit and offers 200 lunches a day, classes in English and French and asylum consultations for hundreds of vulnerable unaccompanied minors in the camp.
More than 170 000 people signed a petition to protect the children's cafe.
The letter sent to the Guardian said its closure "would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are not older than eight."
Two charities, Helping Refugees and L'Auberge des Migrants on Friday estimated that the number in the Jungli camp has grown and exceeded 9 000 people — the highest in history — after a sharp increase in new arrivals during the summer.
