The UN is investigating the use of chemical weapons in Syria.
The UN special commission is investigating the possible use of toxic gas in rebel-held areas of the Syrian city of Aleppo.
All parties to the conflict deny the use of chlorine, but the UN special envoy for Syria, Stefan de Mistura, considers the fact that the incident is indisputable.
Similar statements were made on the eve of the third round of intra-Syrian talks, which are to begin at the end of August in Geneva.
UN experts have launched an investigation into reports of the use of chemical weapons in the Syrian city of Aleppo.
The first information about the terrorist attack using toxic gas, presumably chlorine, appeared on August 2.
Then the opposition said that in the area where a Russian military transport helicopter was shot down the day before, the aircraft dropped bombs with a poisonous substance, but in Moscow these accusations were called a throw-in.
Later, the Russian Defense Ministry accused the opposition group Harakat Nur al-Din al-Zinki of what happened.
Soon it became known that the bombs filled with toxic gas were two.
This was confirmed by the BBC by one of the victims.
“A few minutes later, I smelled the gas, began to burn the eye, it became difficult to breathe,” the newspaper quotes the words of the eyewitness.
As a result of the attack, at least 7 people were killed, 23 were hospitalized.
If the fact of the use of poison gas is confirmed by experts, the actions will be regarded as a war crime.
The UN Special Envoy for Syria Staffan de Mistura told reporters: “There is a lot of evidence that this has really happened.”
The inadmissibility of the use of chlorine for military purposes is prescribed in the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC).
Despite the fact that all parties to the Syrian conflict deny the use of toxic gases, in 2015 human rights activists recorded 35 cases of the use of chlorine by the Syrian army against the “moderate opposition”.
The situation in Aleppo is complicated by the fact that the shelling of its areas is carried out daily, and terrorists prevent the withdrawal of residents from the city.
According to Reuters, the UN expects Russia to establish a “humanitarian pause” in military operations.
The current regime of the daily three-hour lull in the organization considers “insufficient to help almost 2 million civilians trapped”.
Staffan de Mistura’s humanitarian adviser Jan Egeland said a 48-hour ceasefire would be required to deliver aid and evacuate the sick and wounded to the city.
“We have to send voluminous cargoes from a convoy of trucks in an area where roads are almost destroyed, and those that remain are mined,” Egeland said. “But the Russian delegation confirmed its readiness to sit down with us at the negotiating table.”
Consultations in Geneva between representatives of the United States and Russia on the establishment of a “humanitarian pause” continue.
How Russia opened the “humanitarian windows” in Aleppo
In the context of the ongoing battle for Aleppo, Russia, Russia on 11 August announced the introduction of a three-hour cessation of hostilities, which will operate daily from Thursday.
The creation of “humanitarian windows” is designed to provide conditions for the delivery of medicines, food and basic necessities to the city.
The decision of the Ministry of Defense of the Russian Federation was made against the background of increasing international pressure on Moscow with the requirement to curtail the military operation and contribute to the resumption of the negotiation process.
As a result of a series of explosions in the resorts of Thailand killed four people.
Several explosions occurred in southern Thailand on Friday morning.
As a result of the attack, four people were killed, 19 were injured.
The epicenter of the explosions fell on the city of Hua-Hin.
Among the victims were ten foreigners, citizens of four states, there are no Russians among them.
None of the terrorist groups has yet claimed responsibility for the incident, but the interior Ministry of the country hastened to declare that the Islamists are not involved in it.
Several people have already been detained on suspicion of organizing the explosions.
According to preliminary data of the local police, the scale and features of the explosions indicate that they were directed against the military heads of the country.
The attacks occurred at popular tourist resorts, including Patong Beach in the Phuketa and Hua-Hin, Trang and Surat Thani.
After the arrival of the military junta in the country in 2014, economic growth fell from 7.2% (2012) to 2.8% (2015), but tourism remained one of the few industries that demonstrated development.
In 2016, the country has already been visited by 14 million people, which is 1.5 million more than in 2015.
The first suspects in the preparation and organization of attacks have already been detained, police colonel Krisana Patanacharoen said.
It is too early to talk about targets, he added, but the Ministry of Internal Affairs of the country "sure that they are not connected with international extremist groups."
It is too early to draw conclusions, - said Mr. Patanacharoen. -
But we know for sure that these incidents are not directly related to any kind of terrorism, in fact, these are local sabotage, and we are trying to identify those who stood behind them.
The explosions occurred on the birthday of Queen of Thailand Sycrite.
The Thai junta considers the protection of the monarchy one of its main priorities, so the incident is most likely directed against it.
According to Police General Sithich Srisopaparanorat, the bombs were detonated remotely with a difference of half an hour.
They were hidden inside trees on busy streets filled with tourists dining in restaurants.
It is already known that one of the four victims was a Thai girl who sold street food.
The identities of the other victims are still unknown, but it is known that they are residents of four foreign states.
According to the Royal Thai Police, among them four German citizens, three Dutch citizens, two Italian citizens and an Austrian citizen.
There are no Russians among the victims of the explosions, the press service of Rosturizm reported.
Local experts also associate the explosions with the referendum held on August 7, in which 61.4% of the country's population supported the draft of the new constitution.
It was prepared by the commission for the drafting of the constitution, appointed by the military junta.
Voters had to decide whether they supported a system in which the upper house of parliament was fully appointed by the military and had a significant role in the election of the country's prime minister.
The new system was adopted and will be tested for the first time in the 2017 parliamentary elections.
Recall that on May 22, 2014, a military coup took place in Thailand under the leadership of the commander of the army of the country, Prayuth Chan-Ocha.
The army was prompted by the ongoing political crisis and the lack of progress in the negotiations between the government and the opposition.
The military created the National Council for Peace and Order, imposed a curfew and censorship, dispersed the protesters and the upper house of parliament.
How Bangkok is in a state of emergency
The Thai government, led by Prime Minister Yingluck Shinawatra, in January 2014 announced a state of emergency in Bangkok and the provinces adjacent to the capital.
The special regime lasted 60 days.
There were two explosions in Bangkok.
In January 2014, in the center of Bangkok, at the Victory Monument, where one of the main protests took place, two explosions occurred, as a result of which 28 people were injured, five of them were in critical condition.
The explosions were made by unknown people on motorcycles.
The authorities have stepped up security measures in the capital and recruited military forces to protect the demonstrators.
In the Dry Log began the development of conditions.
As it became known to Kommersant, the government is invited to agree on a draft of the auction for the Sukhoi Log gold deposit with the preservation of two key restrictions.
It is proposed to prevent a company where 25% and more is owned by foreigners, and those applicants whose capital will not be at least 25% of state participation.
Industry participants do not expect the government to rewrite the terms, noting that many players are not at risk of taking on a complex and expensive project.
The auction can be announced in August, and will be held in October.
The Ministry of Natural Resources submitted to the government a draft order and auction conditions for the largest undeveloped gold deposit in Russia Suha Log (Irkutsk region, reserves and resources - 130 million ounces), two Kommersant sources familiar with the situation told.
The project was introduced on Wednesday evening, one of them clarifies.
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed to Kommersant that the project was submitted to the government.
The representative of Deputy Prime Minister Alexander Khloponin, who oversees the subsoil use, told Kommersant that the project had not yet been received to the official’s office.
"The auction can be announced in August, immediately after the release of the government's order, and taking into account the deadline for collecting applications of potential participants (at least 45 days), the tender may take place in October," the Ministry of Natural Resources said.
According to Kommersant, the project retains two key requirements for potential participants, prescribed in the version, which was sent for approval to ministries and FOIVs in July (Kommersant has).
The first is the presence of applicants in the capital of at least 25% of state participation.
The second is the denial of access to the auction for companies under the control of foreign investors, based on the understanding of FZ-57 on foreign investments in strategic societies.
According to the two articles of the Federal Law specified in the draft, as Kommersant already wrote on August 2, companies whose beneficiaries (25% of shares and above) are not tax residents of the Russian Federation or have dual citizenship may not be allowed to the auction.
The government has the right to impose such restrictions, since the Dry Log refers to the subsoil of federal significance (reserves of more than 50 tons of gold).
The Ministry of Natural Resources confirmed that the project “contains restrictions on the admission of foreign companies,” but refused to comment on the details before the government’s orders.
The demand for state participation in the capital of the auction participants was put forward by the Irkutsk region, Kommersant in December 2015 in the Ministry of Natural Resources and was later confirmed by the governor of the region Sergey Levchenko, noting that it was sent to the Ministry of Natural Resources by his predecessor Sergei Eroshchenko, “who had agreements on investment projects with Rostec”.
Who lobbied for the restriction on the admission of foreigners, the interlocutors of “Kommersant” do not specify.
“But this is in the spirit of the time: not to give control in the largest gold deposit in Russia against the background of Western sanctions,” says the interlocutor of Kommersant, familiar with the preparation of the auction.
The head of the Ministry of Natural Resources Sergey Donskoy on August 1 said that foreigners “can go to the consortium” if the applicants will attract them “as a financial structure, technological partners.”
The interlocutors of Kommersant consider it unlikely that the government will adjust the conditions.
The main contender for Sukha Log in the industry is the consortium of the largest gold miner of the Russian Federation PJSC Polyus, controlled by the son of Suleiman Kerimov Said, and Rostec.
As Kommersant wrote, in July, the partners created the joint venture SL Gold, where Polyus has 51% of shares, the structure of Rostec RT-Gr has 49%.
Rostec declined to comment, the Polys told Kommersant that "certainly interested in this asset" and have all the necessary competencies and resources for its development.
"But the final decision on the possibility and format of our participation will be made after the announcement of the conditions," the "Polyus" added.
ALROSA can participate in the auction, but the decision is up for the government of the Russian Federation, Kommersant sources said.
The possibility of participation in the development of Sukhoi Log was stated by the Russian GV Gold and the Canadian Kinross, which develops assets in Chukotka, while Polymetal and Nordgold, according to Kommersant, are not interested in the asset.
The head of the Union of gold mines of the Russian Federation Sergey Kashuba in December 2015 estimated “Kommersant” investments in the Sukhoi Log at $ 2.5-4 billion.
Most of the potential applicants are deterred not only by the volume of investments, but also by the complexity of the project: serious reconnaissance of reserves and technologies with complex ores are needed, Kommersant’s interlocutors in the industry explain.
