The Spiritual Administration of Muslims (DUM) of Tatarstan refuses to use the Russian language in mosques.
Yesterday, the plenum of the Duma obliged its imams to conduct Friday sermons only in Tatars to force the young Tatars to “study their native language”.
The department says that this “in no case infringes” the rights of Muslims of other nationalities.
In some mosques, Kazan complain that the Tatar language is not understood by up to 60% of parishioners, including foreign students, migrants and the Tatars themselves.
The imams fear that their sermons in Tatar "will not reach the entire audience."
Yesterday, the plenum of the Duma of Tatarstan unanimously decided to hold Friday sermons in the mosques of the republic only in the Tatar language.
As stated by the mufti of Tatarstan Kamil Samigullin, this should be an incentive for young Tatars “to learn their native language.”
“For those who say that it is “heavy”, in every large mosque we intend to organize the lessons of the Tatar language absolutely free of charge,” said Simigullin.
He added that “the decision has already come into force” and today in all mosques preaching “should be already in the Tatar language.”
He recalled that the DUM of Tatarstan publishes the magazine "Shura" with typical sermons in the Tatar language.
The imam, who does not speak Tatar well enough, “can be thoroughly prepared for them.”
The DUM of Tatarstan unites more than a thousand parishes in all municipalities of the republic.
According to the mufti, Friday's sermons are conducted exclusively in the Tatar language.
At the same time, in Kazan, a number of mosques previously used mainly Russian.
In particular, as the mufti pointed out, this was practiced in the Burnaev mosque, Zakabannoy and Enyer.
However, Mr. Mukhametshin stressed, the leadership sets the task that all students have the knowledge of both state languages of the republic, regardless of nationality.
"There can be no question of any infringement of non-tatar Muslims," Mr. Mukhametshin stressed, explaining that the sermon itself "is not obligatory, the main part of the prayer."
At the same time, the prayer itself will continue to be read in Arabic, lectures and lessons in Russian will be preserved in mosques.
At the same time, Rafik Mukhametshin told Kommersant that there was no serious threat of ousting the Tatar language from mosques.
In addition to Russian and Tatar other languages, for example, Uzbek or Tajik, according to him, are not used in sermons in the republic.
The decision of the DUM was actively supported by the Executive Committee of the World Congress of Tatars (CGT).
The head of the executive committee of the CCP Rinat Zakirov told Kommersant: "The Mosques are an important part of our national life."
It would be sad if the Tatar language had left this sphere.
He noted that the conduct of sermons only in the Tatar language "the desire of the imams themselves", but the executive committee of the CGT "consider it right."
The imams interviewed by Kommersant, who preached in Russian, are ready to fulfill the decision of the Duma, but believe that the parishioners will have difficulties with the understanding of the clergy.
Both Tatars and Russians go to the mosque.
Many people don’t understand the language.
Of course, it will be exubiding.
"We will have to rebuild," says the imam of the Burnaev Mosque Farhat Mavletdinov.
According to him, preaching in the Russian language is closer to even many Tatars, since "Russian in schools, and in kindergartens, on the radio - everywhere initially."
However, he believes that the mosque will be able to continue lessons and lectures in Russian, which are held on other days.
We rely on God.
Allah will show a way out of this situation,” he concluded.
But about 60% of us do not know the Tatar language.
These are Uzbeks, and Tajiks, and Azerbaijanis.
There are a lot of foreign students coming to us: Africans, Arabs.
“Therefore, we have been switching to Russian for four years,” the imam says.
He believes that in the Tatar language, sermons will “reach a narrower circle and will not reach the entire audience.”
But we will obey the decision of the plenum.
The result of the sermons will be different.
But time will tell.
“For example, it will only be easier for me, because the Tatar language is my native language,” concluded Gabdullah Galiullin.
The former director of the FSIN was put on trial
The Moscow Prosecutor’s office approved the indictment on the criminal case investigated by the GSU of the TFR on embezzlement of budget funds allocated for the needs of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
The former head of the prison department Alexander Reimer and his deputy will appear before the court, causing damage to the Federal Penitentiary Council in the amount of more than 2.7 billion rubles.
The Moscow prosecutor's office sent a criminal case to the Zamoskvoretsky District Court against the former director of the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia Alexander Reimer, his former deputy Nikolai Krivolapov, as well as the director of the FSU "Center for Information and Technical Support and Communications of the Federal Penitentiary Service" (FSUE TSIOS) Viktor Defined.
Depending on the role and degree of participation in the commission of crimes, they are accused of the GSU of the TFR in Moscow. 3 tbsp. 285 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (abuse of official powers, which entailed grave consequences), p. 4 tbsp. 159 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (fraud committed using its official position, as part of an organized group, on an especially large scale).
In addition, Krivolapov is charged under h. 1 tbsp. 222 of the Criminal Code of the Russian Federation (illegal acquisition and storage of ammunition).
According to the TFR, in 2010-2012, these persons fraudulently stole budget funds allocated by the Federal Penitentiary Service to provide the department with electronic monitoring systems of controlled persons, the so-called electronic bracelets.
To steal budget money, the group members developed a scheme according to which the enterprise controlled by them, FSUE TSITS, with which the relevant state contracts were concluded, produced technical means of control and supervision, including “electronic bracelets”, and sold at prices overestimated several times.
Despite the fact that FSUE TSITOs had no production equipment, buildings, facilities for the placement of production facilities, allowing to create a completed cycle of production of "electronic bracelets", five state contracts worth more than 3.3 billion rubles were concluded between it and the Federal Penitentiary Service of Russia.
As a result of this scheme, more than 2 billion rubles were on the accounts of the Samara branch of FSUE, of which 1.2 billion rubles. was stolen.
According to the investigation, more than 140 million rubles. Mr. Reimer personally received cash-out funds in his office from one of the accomplices, the criminal case against which was allocated to a separate proceeding.
Nikolai Krivolapov, who participated in the fraud, was found of the unknown origin of the cartridge to the award pistol, which allowed him to bring an additional charge.
In this case, the volume of which amounted to 133 volumes, the FSIN to the accused filed a claim for compensation for material damage in the amount of 2.7 billion rubles.
Footballer Hakan Shukur is suspected of involvement in the putsch.
The Turkish authorities issued a warrant for the arrest of a former football player, and then member of parliament Hakan Shukur and conducted searches in two homes of his family.
The star of Turkish football of the 1990's - early 2000's striker Hakan Shukur is wanted by the authorities of the country in connection with the attempted coup that occurred last month.
