WSJ: the United States is considering the introduction of sanctions against Russia due to the hacking of the servers of the Democrats.
US officials are considering the introduction of new sanctions against Russia in response to the hacking of the servers of the Democratic party, writes The Wall Street Journal, citing sources.
Reportedly, for the imposition of sanctions, the administration of US President Barack Obama will have to officially blame the attack on servers of Russia or the hackers supported by the Russian authorities.
According to sources, the FBI and other American intelligence agencies are almost confident in Russia’s involvement in a cyber attack.
The WSJ notes that the US usually prefers not to indicate by name those who carry out hacker attacks.
The exception is the hacking of the Sony Entertainment Pictures database in 2014, the responsibility for which was officially assigned to the DPRK.
Last year, however, Obama issued a decree simplifying the imposition of sanctions on those who carry out or facilitate cyber attacks.
Initially, it was directed against China, but can be used against other countries.
The process of making a decision on sanctions can be long, the newspaper writes.
Even if officials came to the conclusion that the hackers acted with the support of Russia, before making a decision on the disclosure of information, they will have to weigh the possible consequences.
They have to determine whether the incident is serious enough to exacerbate tensions in bilateral relations because of it.
Earlier it was reported that the administration of Barack Obama allows the possibility of applying sanctions against the state, whose hackers hacked the servers of the national Committee of the Democratic party.
WikiLeaks has published e-mails of the Democratic National Committee.
The media reported that hackers working with the Russian authorities may be involved in the hack.
In the Kremlin, such reports were called absurd.
FAS fined Google almost half a billion rubles
The reason was the violation of competition in the mobile application market.
The antimonopoly proceedings were initiated by Yandex.
The Russian company claimed that Google provides smartphone manufacturers with access to Android components on terms that prohibited pre-installation of applications from other developers, in particular, from Yandex.
The FAS found confirmation of these claims and established, the company abused the dominant position in the market and imposed on the manufacturers of mobile devices the installation along with the Google Play store other applications.
According to the results of the audit, the Federal Antimonopoly Service decided to punish Google, said the deputy head of the FAS Alexey Dotsenko.
The fine must be paid within 60 days after the entry into force of the decree.
The FAS concluded that the law on the protection of competition must be observed by all companies, including transnational corporations.
In turn, Google intends to first study the decision and only then will be determined with further actions: to execute it or challenge it.
The Federal Antimonopoly Service recognized the company as a violator of the competition law in September last year and ordered to adjust the contracts until December 18.
However, Google did not agree to this.
Since then, the company and the department have been conducting legal proceedings.
The FAS noted that, despite the fine, they are discussing with Google the possibility of concluding a settlement agreement.
This measure will not lead to anything.
This opinion was expressed by the leading analyst of Mobile research group Eldar Murtazin.
Murtazin also noted that the fine will not affect either users or the competitiveness of the corporation.
