“Generation Protests” in Ethiopia, a longtime U.S. ally
Furious protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia faced fierce opposition from the government.
Witnesses say dozens of protesters were fatally wounded in clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia really on the brink of schism?
Over the past decade, it has been one of the most stable countries in Africa, a firm ally of the West with a rapidly developing economy.
But in recent months, anti-government protests have shaken the country, spreading to an increasing number of its territories.
Over the past week alone, thousands of people have taken to the streets, demanding radical political change.
According to human rights defenders, the government’s response was fierce.
Witnesses claimed that police officers shot down dozens of unarmed demonstrators.
Video footage from the protests, allegedly shot at the end of last year or earlier this year, shows how security officers beat young people with sticks when they were put on their hands against the wall.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights is now calling for a thorough investigation.
“It has always been difficult to keep this country from disintegrating, and it will continue to be even more difficult,” said Rashid Abdi, head of the Africa Horn project in an international research crisis group.
Ethiopia is the second densely populated country in Africa after Nigeria, and its stability is maintained by the West.
U.S. military and intelligence services work closely with Ethiopians to combat terrorist threats in the region, especially in Somalia, and virtually no country in Africa receives such support from the West.
The economy of Ethiopia is developing at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly – there is even a new suburban train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And its streets, as a rule, quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia was hardly a model of democracy – human rights organizations are constantly mentioned about government repressions – the opposition on the territory of the state was suppressed, due to the fact that dissidents were actually silenced.
Many of them were exiled, imprisoned, murdered or driven into remote deserts.
But that can change.
“If people are constantly suppressed and left by options but to protest, an uprising will rise,” said Seyum Teshomet, a lecturer at the University of Central Ethiopia.
All the young people are protesting.
The generation is protesting.
Complaints are numerous, ranging from land use, ending with the seizure of power by the government coalition.
After the widely criticized elections last year, the government party and its allies completely ousted the opposition and now control 100 percent of Parliament.
At the same time, tensions along the border with Eritrea are growing; the struggle for this uncertain, disputed border has claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups that have been more or less destroyed in recent years, such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to use unrest and rearrangement.
A number of factors explain why bitter feelings, a few years boiling in the depths of the soul, flare up now.
The first, it would seem, is completely harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last couple of years, a large number of Ethiopians were able to communicate on social networks, as cheap smartphones have become commonplace, and the Internet service has become better.
Even when the government shuts down access to Facebook and Twitter, as often happens, especially during protests, many people still find the opportunity to communicate through the proxy servers that hide where they are.
Several young Ethiopians said that this is how they organized for the protests.
The second, that there is more solidarity between Oromo and Amhara, the two largest Ethiopian ethnic groups.
Oroma and Amhara are not natural allies.
For centuries, Amhara, of Ethiopia’s predominantly Christian highlands, flourished in politics and business, exploiting Oromo, many of whom are Muslims and live in lowland areas.
But it's also changing.
“We will act together under a single principle,” said Mulatu Gemechu, the leader of Oromo.
The largest protests took place in the Amhara and Oromo areas.
Many of Amhara and Oromo feel that Ethiopia is unfairly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which makes up about 6 percent of the population and controls military and intelligence services, trade and politics.
The third cause of the excitement is the loss of Meles Zenaui.
Meles, a former rebel leader, served as Prime Minister of Ethiopia for 17 years, until his death from an unknown disease in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could foresee danger.
Analysts say that he especially skillfully recognized the first signals of discontent and used scouts to obtain data and neutralize opponents.
“The current regime lacks common sense,” Abdi, an analyst of conflict situations, said.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Desalein, appeared nowhere and took the place of Meles.
Unlike Meles, who was originally from the Tigray region in northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is a southerner.
Analysts say he does not enjoy the trust of the security services controlled by Tigray.
Many fear that as a result, this will lead to even more bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such unrest was in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts said appeared to be the elections that the government has frozen and then faked the results.
In the ensuing repressions, many Protestants were killed, albeit in less than the last months, and this period of unrest has gone relatively quickly.
Development experts expressed appreciation for Ethiopia ' s leaders for the vision of infrastructure, such as the new long-distance train and significant successes in the fight against poverty.
But it is clear that this did not stop the growth of internal discontent by the Ethiopian government.
It takes a dangerous ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in Gondar, a city in Amhar, attacked Tigray-owned enterprises, and anti-Tigray hatred on social media became comprehensive.
Analysts say the protesters put the United States and other Western allies in an uncomfortable position.
The U.S. government used Ethiopia as a base for unmanned flights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently announced it had closed the base.
On the one hand, it is clear that the West wants to support democracy, but on the other hand, he does not want his ally to lose strength in an already unstable region.
“And it will be difficult to pass on this stretched rope,” Abdi said.
