NASA's Climate Model: Venus Was Once Inhabited
Venus may have been habitable, according to estimates of the new NASA climate model.
Scientists from the Nasov Institute for the Study of Goddard’s Space Developed a Model to Study the Past Venus, using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climatologists.
The model was designed to determine whether on Venus, with its hot waterless surface and an atmosphere oversaturated with carbon dioxide, could ever exist conditions like Earth.
Scientists previously assumed that the low speed of rotation of Venus is explained by its dense atmosphere.
But the last simulation suggests that Venus could probably have a rarefied atmosphere like an earth, and still rotate slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
There were more drylands on the planet than on Earth, but once there was enough water and enough geographical variability to create conditions for life and prevent rapid evaporation.
Early Venus also benefited the sun, which was 30 percent dim.
“According to the GISS model, Venus’ slow rotation is setting its dayside to the sun for almost two months at a time,” GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio explained in a print message.
This warms the surface of the planet and produces rain that creates a thick layer of clouds acting as an umbrella protecting the planet’s surface from a substantial portion of solar heat.
The result is average climatic temperatures, which, surprisingly, are slightly cooler than these days on Earth.
The model shows the history of Venus, similar to the development that was previously assumed by experts in the study of planets.
Despite the fact that once Venus may have been habitable, it has been exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation for several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapor was burned by ultraviolet radiation.
When its hydrogen evaporated, only a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with a deadly greenhouse effect remained – that is, Venus, as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new climate model Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
