Kepler Measures the Rotation Rate of Stars in the Pleiades Cluster
The latest mission of the Kepler Space Telescope helped astronomers to collect the most complete catalog of speeds of rotation of stars included in the Pleiades cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, and how periods of rotation relate to planet formation.
“We hope that by matching our results with other star clusters, we learn more about the relationship between the mass of the star, its age and even the history of its solar system,” said Louise Riballe, a researcher at the Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis at the California Institute of Technology.
The Cluster of Pleiades is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many stars in the cluster are now only reaching maturity; they were born about 125 million years ago.
They rotate as fast as they never will be.
At their peak rotation speeds, these growing stars emit large amounts of stellar wind.
By traveling through the magnetic fields of stars, these winds have a braking effect on the stars.
As the star ages, its speed of rotation begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star, tracking the time between the appearance of recognizable star spots, such as sunspots.
The latest reciprocating catalog suggests that more massive stars orbit more slowly than less massive stars.
Riball compares stars to dancers: larger ones make pirouettes more slowly than smaller ones.
“In ballet, we observe that those that rotate slowly are usually more massive, while those that rotate faster usually refer to very light stars,” Riballe said.
Since the cluster of Pleiades is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the properties of stars with the speed of rotation.
“The Pleiada Starskombo provides a starting point for theoretical models of rotation of stars, both younger and older,” Riballe said.
We still want to learn a lot about how, where and why the stars slow down their speed of their rotation and hang their “dance shoes” on their nail, figuratively speaking.
Riballe and her colleagues detailed their latest analysis of the Pleiades rotation speeds in three new articles, which will soon be published in an Astronomical Journal.
