Contrary to the international trend of rising inequality, it is declining in Namibia.
Compared to the 1993 indicator, Gini, which is a standard indicator of income inequality, fell by 15 points.
Then, 23 years ago, this figure was one of the highest in the world.
Poverty fell from 69% in 1993 to less than 30 percent.
The number of people living in extreme poverty (less than $1.90 per day) has also decreased, from nearly 53% to less than 23 percent.
Namibia also has the highest freedom of speech rating in Africa, according to Reporters Without Borders.
The country was far ahead of the United States and other rich states.
