Of course, Namibia has some problems.
The unemployment rate, at least by traditional valuation methods, remains quite high - almost 28%.
And, like other countries in the region, Namibia has a high incidence of HIV/AIDS, nearly 17 per cent of the population is infected.
The World Bank estimates that Namibia is among the above-average countries, but the authorities insist that their state is actually a developing country.
Namibia certainly faces some of the difficulties inherent in poorly developed economies.
The state has to develop a very large and arid country with a small population.
On the territory of the country in the deserts live isolated nomadic tribes of hunter-gatherers, which in one way or another should be integrated into modern society, without losing their identity.
The integration of people who were on the periphery of the world economy a quarter of a century ago is not an easy task for any country.
For Namibia, this is even more difficult: just like any other country in the world, it faces the effects of climate change.
However, Namibia did not think to give up, the country solves the problems facing it.
Almost immediately after independence, the authorities began to create a diversified economy and a cohesive society.
It is noteworthy that competing political factions came together to work for the common good.
Indeed, Namibia provides cheap medical care not only to its own citizens, but also to its neighbors.
About 15-20% of visitors to medical institutions in the northern regions of Namibia are Angolan citizens.
