In addition, the Government of Namibia has rightly reasoned that rich natural resources can easily become a curse by fostering the enrichment of the few at the expense of many.
The authorities understand that the income from the natural wealth of Namibia must be invested in infrastructure and production capacities.
They are also aware that it would be irresponsible not to seek to obtain maximum profit from the sale of the country’s resources, and revise investment laws and mining contracts to make sure it is.
Transparency is crucial to this process, so the government’s strong support for freedom of speech is so important.
As the head of state Hage Gaingob noted, the media often say what he does not like.
But after the struggle for the freedom from apartheid in South Africa, Namibia must defend the freedoms received, the president said.
Not all of Namibia’s key resources are exhausted.
Some, such as fishing, are revolving, and the Government is making every effort to preserve and strengthen them.
Every year more than a million foreign tourists visit the country.
Namibia shows that even those countries that begin with serious flaws – racism, the colonial system, inequality and low level of development – can embark on a path to common prosperity.
Its achievement deserves international recognition and imitation.
Many have heard of the "Gold of Varna" - the oldest gold objects created by man (4600 - 4200 BC).
Perhaps, it was the loudest archaeological sensation of the 1970s: in Bulgaria, during the excavations of the Varna necropolis, a fantastic number of gold artifacts were found - more than three thousand total weight of 6 kilograms.
Only one burial, known as "grave No. 43", was extracted 990 gold objects with a total weight of more than 1.5 kg.
However, the official status of the oldest gold in the world may soon move to a nondescript bead, found by archaeologists in July of this year.
And again in Bulgaria - in a prehistoric settlement known as Tell Yuniche.
Unlike Varna, the port city, Tell Yuniche is located away from the sea, near the village of Yunazite, Pazardzhik district.
Bustina is a gold stripe folded into a ring.
Yavor Boyajdzhiev, the head of excavations in Tell Yuniche, dated the discovery of 4600 BC and stated that she was older than Varna’s gold by at least 200 years.
The treasures of Varna, we recall, date back to about the same period, 4600 - 4200. BC.
There are no technologies that allow to date the metal with impeccable accuracy at present.
Why does the belief in which gold is older?
Obviously, Professor Boyadzhiev knows more than he told Reuters: “I am quite sure that Yunazite gold is older than Varna’s gold.”
This is a finding of extreme importance: in appearance it is a tiny object, but it is large enough to take a proper place in history.
In an interview with Reuters, Boyadzhiev said that in the near future scientists will analyze the composition of the metal, as well as re- and more thoroughly study the archaeological layer where the gold artifact was found.
This will help to date the bead with the maximum possible accuracy.
The place of discovery also explains a lot.
Tell Yunaztake is a famous settlement, even if you have never heard of it.
Currently, Tell Yunazite is considered the oldest "city" of Europe.
Tell was founded by the descendants of people who migrated to Europe from Anatolia (modern Turkey) in the 7 millennium BC.
Over the following centuries, the processing of metals developed rapidly in this region, from the development of the first metallurgical skills to the creation of a full-fledged industry.
In the domestic historiography for this archaeological community there is a special name: the Balkan-Carpathian Metallurgical Province.
In 5 millennia BC, urban-type settlements began to arise around the centers of metalworking.
Now they are called the oldest cities in Europe.
Of these, Tell Yunocite is perhaps the most ancient, since the artifacts of 4900 BC were found here.
I would call Tell Yuniche the prototype of a modern city, although it is a very ancient settlement, even compared to Mesopotamia.
“This is the place older than Sumer by a thousand years,” says Boyadzhiev, referring to the generally accepted opinion that urban culture originated in the south of Mesopotamia – modern Iraq.
There were the first cities in the usual sense of the word.
The excavations of Tell Yunazite have been conducted since 1976.
During this time, archaeologists have excavated almost 12 hectares, which is about a third of the estimated total area of the settlement.
The remains of the fortress wall were found, which once reached three meters in height.
Little has been preserved from houses and workshops, but archaeologists clearly distinguish streets, public buildings, urban dense buildings, a “business center” and residential outskirts.
Tell Yunactace is often called the "Bird City": dozens of clay figurines of birds were found here.
All birds are depicted in a state of rest, hence the assumption that they were not decorative objects, but the object of a local cult.
"Avian City" was destroyed around 4100 BC - perhaps by Indo-European tribes that came from the northeast.
Nomads had no cities, but there were horses and weapons.
Three-meter fortress walls did not stop them.
Archaeologists have found obvious signs of a severe massacre: the remains of old people, women and children with traces of wounds inflicted by live axes were found inside the houses.
New findings and new facts appear annually, changing the usual ideas about the ancient history of mankind.
Bulgarian archaeologists are increasingly talking not about individual cultures, but about the “lost” first civilization of Europe, which originated in the Balkans.
A powerful stimulus in the search for this civilization was the "Varden gold", found relatively recently, in 1972.
It is logical that Varna’s gold luxury had to precede something—something like a tiny golden bead created in Tell Yunic.
